### 4. Fully Adaptive Routing Ethernet (FARE) & FARE in MPSON
*   **Presenter:** Xiaohu Xu
*   **Slides:** 
    *   [1-5-1. Fully Adaptive Routing Ethernet (FARE)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-idr-sessa-1-5-1-fully-adaptive-routing-ethernet-fare-00)
    *   [1-5-2. Fully Adaptive Routing Ethernet in Multi-Plane Scale-Out Networks (FARE in MPSON)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-idr-sessa-1-5-2-fully-adaptive-routing-ethernet-in-multi-plane-scale-out-networks-fare-in-mpson-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   Xiaohu Xu discussed FARE in Multi-Plane Scale-Out Networks (MPSON) for AI/GPU clusters. Because there are no inter-plane links, the SmartNIC/RDMA NIC needs to perform weighted ECMP across planes.
    *   Scaling host routes to 100k+ GPUs is problematic for NIC memory. He proposed two routing reduction techniques: route aggregation with unreachability notification (using past bandwidth set to zero, or UPA), and Prefix ORF with FIB suppression on leaf switches.
    *   Krishna Swamy questioned why a default route is not sufficient for the NIC. Xiaohu Xu and Jeff Tantsura clarified that AI training clusters are "rail-optimized" and traffic must exit via specific rails to prevent performance degradation; thus, default routes cannot be used.
    *   On the base FARE draft, updates were added regarding multi-BGP session granularity and forwarding over tunnels. Xiaohu Xu requested a Working Group adoption call. Jeffrey Haas reminded the author that the draft currently exceeds the IETF 5-author limit and must be trimmed.

