### 10. Canonical Textual Representation of BGP Path Attributes
*   **Presenter:** Martin Belz
*   **Slides:** [1-9. Canonical textual representation of BGP Path Attributes](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-idr-1-9-canonical-textual-representation-of-bgp-path-attributes-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   Martin Belz presented an individual proposal to standardize the textual representations of BGP path attributes (such as extended communities, which are formatted inconsistently across vendors—e.g., Bird's use of parentheses vs. colons). Standardizing this is critical for human readability in YANG-based streaming telemetry.
    *   He requested co-authors and proposed working with GROW's YANG communities work to define a JSON template that allows dynamic loading of formatting definitions without code changes.
    *   Luca (NLnet Labs) supported the work and volunteered to test it, suggesting that Martin consult with Colin (maintainer of BGP dump) to handle legacy edge cases.
    *   Jeffrey Haas supported the effort, noting that standardizing these mappings would be highly beneficial for the BGP YANG module and future implementations.

