### 12. Threat Model for BGP Color Extended Community
*   **Presenter:** Yuan Zhang
*   **Slides:** [1-11. Threat Model for BGP Color Extended Community](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-idr-sessa-1-11-threat-model-for-bgp-color-extended-community-00)
*   **Discussion:**
    *   Yuan Zhang described the security gap of the BGP Color Extended Community, which is widely used to steer traffic across AS boundaries (SR Policy, BGP CAR, BGP CT). Currently, BGP color lacks origin attribution and is implicitly trusted, allowing transit networks or hackers to manipulate, inject, or strip color values to redirect traffic.
    *   The draft defines attack classes (injection, re-coloring, stripping) and suggests two directions for future work: a binding mechanism (e.g., tying color to origin AS via RPKI or BGPsec extensions) and a freshness mechanism (e.g., timestamps/sequence numbers).
    *   Susan Hares suggested exploring BGP community containers to bind these values, noting security authorization belongs in RPKI.
    *   Jeffrey Haas recommended coordinating with the GROW working group, which is currently updating community scrubbing operational security documents.

